srs-inst:gp-a1-056-er-and-liang a srs-kg:GrammarPoint ;
    rdfs:label "'Er' and 'liang'"@en ;
    srs-kg:cefrLevel "A1" ;
    srs-kg:explanation "In Chinese, there are two words for \"two.\" They are 二 (èr) and 两 (liǎng), and each is used in different circumstances. 二 is used in numbers (the digit \"2\"). This is used generally in numbers, when counting to ten, giving out a phone number, and so on. Unlike 两 (liǎng), 二 (èr) is not used to say there are \"two\" of something, and does not generally occur with measure words by itself. 两 is used with measure words when specifying quantities. This is when you want to say \"two of something\" or \"both.\""@en ;
    srs-kg:hasExample srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-001,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-002,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-003,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-004,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-005,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-006,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-007,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-008,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-009,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-010,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-011,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-012,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-013,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-014,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-015,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-016,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-017,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-018,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-019,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-020,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-056-er-and-liang-021 ;
    srs-kg:structure "Use 二 (èr) for numbers/digits and 两 (liǎng) with measure words for quantities." .

srs-inst:gp-a1-051-affirmative-negative-question a srs-kg:GrammarPoint ;
    rdfs:label "Affirmative-negative question"@en ;
    srs-kg:cefrLevel "A1" ;
    srs-kg:explanation "This is a common way to form questions by presenting both the positive and negative forms of a verb or adjective. For single-syllable words, the word is repeated with 不 in between (e.g., 去不去). For two-syllable words, it is common to repeat only the first character before 不 (e.g., 喜不喜欢). The verb 有 (yǒu) is a special case, using the structure 有没有, because its negative form is 没有 (méiyǒu)."@en ;
    srs-kg:hasExample srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-051-affirmative-negative-question-001,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-051-affirmative-negative-question-002,
        srs-inst:sent-gp-a1-051-affirmative-negative-question-003,
